metadata.title: Bell OH-58 Kiowa
aws::graph::propositions: # Bell OH-58 Kiowa Retirement and Transfer Information
Media expected Bell OH-58 Kiowa helicopters to go to foreign militaries rather than civil operators due to high operating cost.
By 2015, the United States Army had divested 33 OH-58D Kiowa helicopters.
By January 2016, the United States Army had divested all but two OH-58D Kiowa squadrons.
In June 2016, members of 1st Squadron, 17th Cavalry Regiment, 82nd Combat Aviation Brigade, arrived in South Korea as part of the Bell OH-58 Kiowa's last deployment in United States Army service.
During the year following June 2016, the 1st Squadron, 17th Cavalry Regiment reequipped with AH-64 Apache helicopters.
In January 2017, the last Bell OH-58 Kiowa Warrior helicopters performed their last live fire maneuver before retirement.
Ex-United States Army OH-58D Kiowa helicopters were made available through Excess Defense Article program.
Ex-United States Army OH-58D Kiowa helicopters were made available through foreign military sales (FMS) programs.
In November 2014, Croatia sent a letter of intent for the acquisition of 16 OH-58D Kiowa helicopters.

text:
Media expected OH-58s to go to foreign militaries rather than civil operators due to high operating cost. By 2015, the Army had divested 33 OH-58Ds. By January 2016, the Army had divested all but two OH-58D squadrons. In June 2016, members of 1st Squadron, 17th Cavalry Regiment, 82nd Combat Aviation Brigade, arrived in South Korea as part of the Kiowa's last deployment in U.S. Army service; during the following year, the unit reequipped with AH-64s. In January 2017, the last Kiowa Warrior performed their last live fire maneuver before retirement.
Ex-U.S. Army OH-58Ds were made available through Excess Defense Article and foreign military sales (FMS) programs. In November 2014, Croatia sent a letter of intent for the acquisition of 16 OH-58Ds.
